Main Ideas

  • Holt’s method can capture a trend component

  • Trend can be additive

Main Ideas (cont’d)

  • Trend can be multiplicative

The (Additive) Equation

The Updating Equations

  • Level at time t is a weighted average of the actual value at time t and the level in the previous period, adjusted for trend.

The Updating Equations (cont’d)

  • Trend at time t is a weighted average of the trend in the previous period and the more recent information on the change in level.

Additive VS Multiplicative Trend

Data Example (cont’d)

  • Step 7 (optional): Let’s automate this process and assess .001-.49. First, we create a vector of values from 0.01 to 0.499 with step 0.01.
beta <- seq(0.001, 0.499, 0.001)

Initialization of variable RMSE with a single value NA.

RMSE <- NA

Iterate through all values of vector beta and assess prediction accuracy

library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)
for(i in seq_along(beta)) {
 fcast <- holt(paper_train, beta = beta[i], h = 4)
 RMSE[i] <- accuracy(fcast, paper_test)[2, 2]
}
# turn our RMSE values for beta .001-.49 into a data frame
error <- data_frame(beta, RMSE)


minimum <- filter(error, RMSE == min(RMSE))
minimum
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##    beta  RMSE
##   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 0.029  20.5
# plot RMSE values for beta .001-.49
ggplot(error, aes(beta, RMSE)) +
 geom_line() +
 geom_point(data = minimum, color = "blue", size = 2) +
 ggtitle("beta's impact on simple exponential smoothing forecast errors",
 subtitle = "beta = 0.029 minimizes RMSE")

Data Example (cont’d)
